{\fs20 Students who are preparing for professions in which their primary responsibilities involve motor skill instruction often question the need to study motor control theory. This type of questioning often comes from those who believe their preparation needs to involve only \ldblquote practical\rdblquote  information that will help them carry out their day-to-day responsibilities in the workplace. Unfortunately, this view is often the result of a lack of understanding of the relevance of theory to professional practice. In this section, we will discuss what a theory is and the \u173 ?
relevance of motor control theory for practitioners. One of the goals of this section is to establish why the discussion of motor control theory is presented in this book before the discussion of specific topics related to motor control and learning. }
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 What Is a Theory?\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 If we base our understanding of the term }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i theory}{\fs20  on\u8239 ?how it is commonly used in everyday language, \line we come away with the view that a theory has \u173 ?
little\u8239 ?}{\fs20 relevance to reality. But this view is shortsighted and misleading. In science, a theory helps us understand phenomena and explains the rea\u173 ?
sons why these \u173 ?phenomena exist or behave as they do.\u8239 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Stephen Hawking (1996), the }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
