{\fs20\super 1}{\fs20  these two will provide a sufficient foundation on which to base your introduction to the two prominent motor control theories discussed in this chapter.}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 It is important to note that the theories \u173 ?described here address motor control from a \u173 ?
predominantly }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 behavioral level.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  As you saw in chapter 1, this means \line that they focus on explaining observed be}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 havior }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 without attempting to specify neural-level features of the control process (for examples of neural mod}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 els of motor control, see Bullock &\u8239 ?Grossberg, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 1991; Grossberg }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
& Paine, 2000; }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Rokni & Sompolinsky, 2012;}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  Wolpert & Ghahramani, 2000; Wu, Haugh, Sarnow, & Hitt, 2006). An important goal of behaviorally based motor control }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 theories is to propose laws and prin\u173 ?ciples that gov}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ern coor\u173 ?dinated human motor behavior. A neural-level theory would be expected to describe neural mechanisms or neural mechanism interactions that explain }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 how the nervous system is involved in these behav}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ioral principles (see, for example, Willingham, 1998).}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Coordination\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 An important characteristic of all motor control theories is that they include explanations of how we control coordination. Therefore, it is essential that we establish an understanding of the meaning of the term }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i coordination}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  as it applies to the performance of motor skills. The performance of a motor skill involves a person}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \rquote s organization of the activation of muscles in such a way that the goal of an action can be accomplished. It is this organizational feature that is at the heart of the definition of the term }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 coordination.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  For the purposes of this textbook, we will use as a general definition one provided by Turvey (1990): }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 coordination}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  is the patterning of head, body, and limb movements relative to the patterning of environmental objects and events.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 This definition contains two parts. Each is important to consider further. First, note that the definition specifies that coordination involves }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i patterns of head, body, and/or limb movements.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  Although a common colloquial use of the term }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i coordination}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  relates it to a characteristic of skilled performance, it should not be limited to this use. When used in reference to a movement pattern associated with the perfor-mance of a skill, coordination refers to the organizational relationship of movement characteristics of the head, body, and limb  involved in the perfor-\line mance, }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i regardless of the skill level of the performer.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  This means that when we consider the assessment of movement characteristics of the performance of a skill, it is necessary to consider coordination as referring to the relationship among the head, body, and/or limbs }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i at a specific point in time}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  during the skill performance.\par }{\fs20 As you saw in chapter 2, a common way to portray movement patterns is to represent graphically in an angle-angle diagram the relationship between the displacement patterns of limbs as they move while performing the skill. An example of this type of representation can be seen in figure 5.2}
{\fs20 , where the coordination of the knee and hip joint angles during a soccer kick is shown.\par The second part of the definition states that the pattern of head, limb, and body motion is }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i relative to the pattern of environmental objects and events.}{\fs20  This is important because it establishes the need to consider movement coordination in relation to the context in which the skill is performed. The characteristics of the environmental context constrain the head, body, and limbs to act in certain ways so that the goal of the action can be achieved.}
{\fs20 \par For example, to walk along a pathway, people must adapt their head, body, and limb movement}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
 patterns to the characteristics of the pathway. If, for example, a person is walking on a sidewalk and encounters a tree branch lying across it, he or she must use a new pattern of movements in order to step over the branch. The characteristics of the tree branch will dictate the characteristics of the \u173 ?
movement \u173 ?pattern. If it is small, the person may simply need to adjust the length of a walking stride and take a large step; if it is a large branch, he or she may have to stop walking and climb over it.\par }
\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 The Degrees of Freedom Problem\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Because coordination involves head, body, and limb movement patterns, an important question in the study of motor control is this: }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i How does the nervous system control the many muscles and joints involved in producing a complex movement pattern?}
{\fs20  To answer this question, we must consider an important problem that was first posed by \u173 ?Nicolai Bernstein, a noted Russian physiologist whose work, produced from the 1930s to the 1950s, did not become known to the Western world until 1967. }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 His work continues to influence research and theory}{\fs20  related to motor control. Bernstein proposed that to perform a well-coordinated movement, the nervous system had to solve what he termed the \ldblquote degrees of freedom problem.\rdblquote }
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 degrees of freedom}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  of any system reflect the number of independent components of the system and the number of ways each component can vary. Each component is \ldblquote free\rdblquote  to vary in specific ways, as in the case of the elbow joint, which can vary (i.e., move) in two ways: flexion and extension. The }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 degrees of freedom problem}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  arises when a complex system needs to be organized to produce a specific result. The control problem is as follows: }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 How can an effective yet efficient control system be designed so that a complex system, having many degrees of freedom, is constrained to act in a particular way?}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Consider the following example of the degrees of freedom control problem in a complex mechanical system. A helicopter is designed so that it can fly up or down, to the left or the right, forward or backward, and so on, and at a variety of speeds. If the pilot had to control one switch or lever for each component needed to make the helicopter fly a certain way, the pilot\rquote s job would be overwhelming. Therefore, the helicopter designer reduces the complexity of the task by providing control sticks and pedals that the pilot can manipulate simultaneously with his or her hands and feet. Each stick or pedal controls several functions at once.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 When the nervous system must control the human body so that it performs a complex motor skill, such as }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 climbing a ladder}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 , it faces a degrees of freedom control problem similar to that involving the helicopter. The determination of the actual number of degrees of freedom that must be controlled in \u173 ?
coordinated human movement depends on which level of control we are considering. At one level, we might consider motor units as the elements that must be controlled. At another level, we could consider joints as the element of \u173 ?
interest. Regardless of the control level considered, it becomes evident that for any motor skill, the control problem involved in enabling a person to perform that skill is an enormous one. However, as you will see in chapter 12, when a person practices a skill and progresses from a beginner to a skilled performer, the motor control system solves the degrees of freedom problem in ways that are evident from the changes we can \u173 ?
observe in specific coordination characteristics.\par }\pard\plain \s10\f4\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 OPEN-LOOP AND CLOSED-LOOP \line CONTROL SYSTEMS\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Most theories of motor control incorporate two \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1\u173 ?basic systems of control. These two systems, called \line }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw3 open-loop}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4  and }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd1\expndtw3 closed-loop control \u173 ?
systems}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 ,}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4  are }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 based on mechanical engineering models of control. Rather than provide exact descriptions of the control processes in complex human movement, these two models are general descriptions of different ways the central and peripheral nervous \u173 ?
systems initiate and control action. These models serve as useful guides that illustrate some of the basic components involved in tha}
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 t \line process.\par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Figure 5.3 presents diagrams illustrating simple open-loop and closed-loop control systems. These are the typical diagrams you would see in any general presentation of these types of control systems. Notice that each of these systems has a }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i control \u173 ?center.}{\fs20  The control center is sometimes referred to as an }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i executive.}
{\fs20  An important part of its role is to \u173 ?generate and issue movement instructions to the }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i effectors,}
{\fs20  which, in the human, are the muscles of the limbs, body, and/or head involved in producing the desired movement. }{\fs20
\par }\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb363\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Differences between the Systems\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 These systems differ in two ways. First, a closed-loop control system involves }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 feedback}
{\fs20 , whereas an open-loop system does not. In human movement, the feedback is }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i afferent}{\fs20  information sent by the various sensory receptors to the control center. The purpose of this feedback is to update the control center about the correctness of the movement while it is in progress.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The second important difference between open- and closed-loop control systems relates to the }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1
move\u173 ?ment instructions}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  issued by the control center. In the open-loop system, because feedback is not used in the control of the ongoing movement, the instructions contain all the information necessary for the effectors to carry out the planned movement. Although feedback is produced and available, it is not used to control the ongoing movement. This may be so because feedback is not needed, or because there is not enough time to use feedback to effectively control the movement after it is initiated.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 In the closed-loop system, the movement instructions are quite different. First, the control center \u173 ?
issues an initial instruction to the effectors that is sufficient only to initiate the movement. The actual execution and completion of the movement depend on feedback information that reaches the control center. The feedback provides information about the status of the movement, which serves to enable the \line control center to do one of several things: allow \line the movement to continue as initially instructed, provide additional instructions to \u173 ?
continue the movement in progress, or correct a movement error. }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 It is important to note that one of the drawbacks of the classic diagram of the closed-loop system, as shown in figure 5.3, is that it depicts the movement effectors as the only source for feedback. However, in the actual performance of skills in which the closed-loop control system operates, there are several other sources of sensory feedback, such as the visual and auditory systems. These sources of feedback will be discussed in chapter 6.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s10\f4\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 TWO THEORIES OF MOTOR CONTROL\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 We can classify theories of how the nervous system controls coordinated movement in terms of the relative importance given to movement instructions specified by central components of the control system or by information arising from interactions among the performer, the task, and the environment. Theories that give prominence to movement instructions specified by the central nervous system in the control process have in common some form of memory representation, such as a motor program, that provides the basis for organizing, initiating, and carrying out intended actions. We will discuss a motor program}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \'d0based theory as an example of this type of theory. In contrast, other theories give more influence to information specified by the environment and to the dynamic interaction of this information with information from the task and the body, limbs, and nervous \line system. We will discuss the dynamical systems theory as an example of this type of theory.\par }
\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb124\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Motor Program\'d0Based Theory\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 At the heart of central control}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \'d0oriented theories is the }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
motor program}{\fs20 ,}{\f4\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 a memory-based construct that controls coordinated movement. Various theoretical viewpoints attribute different degrees of control to the motor program. Undoubtedly, the view that best characterizes present-day thinking about the motor program comes from the work of Richard Schmidt (1988, 2003; Schmidt & Lee, 2019). In his \ldblquote schema theory,\rdblquote  Schmidt (1975) proposed that a serious problem with previous views was that they limited the motor \u173 ?
program to controlling specific movements or sequences of movements. To overcome this limitation, Schmidt hypothesized the }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
generalized \line motor program (GMP)}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  as a mechanism that could account for the adaptive and flexible qualities of \u173 ?
human coordinated-movement behavior.\par }\pard\plain \s14\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb270\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Schmidt\rquote s generalized motor program.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 Schmidt proposed that a GMP controls a }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
class of actions,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  rather than specific movements or sequences. He defined a class of actions as a set of different \u173 ?
actions having a common but unique set of features. For Schmidt, these features, which he called }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0
invariant \line features}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 , are the }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \ldblquote signature\rdblquote  of a GMP and form the basis of what is stored in memory. These movement-related features form the basis of what Schmidt (2003) referred to as }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 the fundamental \line }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 pattern of the class of actions.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
 These features remain consistent from one performance of an action to another. In order for a person to produce a specific action to meet the demands of a performance situation, the person must retrieve the appropriate program from memory and then add movement-specific }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 parameters}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 . These are movement-related features of the performances of an action that can be varied from one performance to another.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 An analogy that can help you understand the distinction between invariant features and parameters of a GMP is the distinction between rhythm and tempo in music and dance. A piece of music has a }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i rhythmic structure}{\fs20  that is specified by the time signature, or meter, which is indicated on the written music score, such as 3/4 or 4/4. The first number (which would be the top number on the music score) indicates the number of beats with equal \u173 ?
proportions of time intervals per measure of music. This number establishes the music\rquote s rhythmic structure. The second, or bottom, number specifies which type of note receives one beat, which in the case of the two examples would be the quarter note\'d1that is, the 1/4 note. For the 3/4 meter there are\u8239 ?}
{\fs20 three beats with equal proportions of time intervals in every measure (i.e., the equivalent of three \line quarter notes in each measure); for the 4/4 there are four beats to every measure. In dance, a waltz, for example, has a 3/4 meter, which means it has three beats to every measure and gives it its familiar 1-2-3 sequence of steps. Note, however, that for the waltz, the three beats are not of equal length; the first is long, the second and third are shorter but equal in time. }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i Tempo}{\fs20  refers to the speed at which the music is performed. The same rhythmic structure can be played slowly or fast. You can try this by clapping your hands with one clap for each beat. Try a consistent series of three claps with equal proportions of time intervals between claps, which establishes the rhythmic structure of your clapping. Then clap the same way but faster. Notice that the rhythmic structure doesn\rquote t change even though you increase the speed of the clapping. In this analogy, rhythm in music is analogous to an \u173 ?
invariant feature of the GMP; tempo is analogous to a parameter.}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Invariant features and parameters.}
{\fs20 \u8194\'20Although many possible characteristics could be invariant features of the GMP, one that Schmidt (2003) considered to be the most likely is the }
{\f4\fs20\b\i0 relative time}{\fs20  (which is analogous to rhythm in music) of the components of the skill. Another is the order, or sequence, of the components. The term }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i relative}{\fs20  in }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i relative time}{\fs20  indicates that what is invariant are the percentages, or proportions, of the overall duration, or movement time of the components of a skill.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Figure 5.4 presents an illustration of how to \u173 ?interpret the concept of invariant relative time. Suppose you move the index finger of your hand as quickly as possible to press five keys on a keyboard in sequence. Now, suppose that the four \u173 ?
components of this task (the time intervals between the keys: \line keys 1-2, 2-3, 3-4, 4-5) yield the following movement time (MT) proportions: component 1 takes up \line 30 percent of the total MT (component % = component MT/total MT); component 2, 20 percent; component 3, 40 percent; and component 4, 10 percent. \line If the performance of this skill under typical conditions has an overall duration of 10 sec [represented in part (a) of the figure], then regardless of how much you speed up or slow down this overall duration, the actual amount of movement time for each component changes proportionately. In figure 5.4, \line parts (b) and (c) represent this proportional component change for speeding up the skill [part (b)] and slowing it down [part (c)]. Thus, if you typically perform this skill in 10 sec, then the amount of time you spend performing each component is 3, 2, 4, and \line 1 sec, respectively. If you performed the skill twice as fast, in 5 sec, then each component would change proportionately to be 1.5, 1, 2, and 0.5 sec, respectively. If you slowed down your overall movement time to 15 sec, then each component would change to 4.5, 3, 6, and 1.5 sec, respectively.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Although motor program theory proposes that the invariant features of a GMP are rather fixed from one performance of a skill to another, it also\u8239 ?
holds that there are other features, called }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 parameters,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  that can be varied. Examples include the }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 overall duration }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 and the}{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
muscles}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  used to \u173 ?perform the skill. Skilled performers can easily change these from one performance situation to \u173 ?
another, readily adapting them to the specific \u173 ?requirements of each situation.\par }{\fs20 The following two examples illustrate the relationship between invariant features and parameters. One relates to figure 5.4, which, as just discussed, portrays relative time as an invariant feature. This figure also illustrates the parameter of }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 overall duration.}{\fs20  The normal, faster, and slower speeds in the figure show that a person can change the overall amount of time taken to move without altering the relative time structure of the components of the movement. This type of situation occurs, for example, when a person walks faster or slower than his or her typical speed.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 The second example concerns }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 muscles}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  as parameters. Research evidence shows that whether you sign your name with a pen held in your preferred hand, in the opposite hand, between your toes, or with your teeth, the two signatures have \u173 ?
distinct \u173 ?invariant spatial as well as relative time \u173 ?features (see\u8239 ?Wright, 1990 for an excellent review of this \u173 ?
research). These results suggest that you can\u8239 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 change the muscles involved in writing your \u173 ?
signature without altering the invariant features \u173 ?represented in the generalized motor program. Interestingly, Rijntjes et al. (1999) provided neu\u173 ?
rological evidence for muscles as a movement parameter related to the signing of one\rquote s name by comparing brain regions activated by people signing their name with the finger of the preferred hand and with the big toe. Additional evidence and examples of muscles as parameters will be discussed in chapter 13, when we consider the topic of bilateral transfer.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Schmidt}{\*\cs51\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0
\rquote s schema theory.}{\fs20 \u8194\'20A formalized theory of how the GMP operates to control coordinated movement is Schmidt\rquote s schema theory (Schmidt, 1975, 1988, 2003). A }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 schema}{\fs20  is a rule or set of rules that serves to provide the basis for a decision. It is developed by abstracting important pieces of information from related experiences and combining \line them into a type of rule. For example, your concept of }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i dog}{\fs20  is the result of seeing many different types of dogs and developing a set of rules that will allow you to identify correctly as a \ldblquote dog\rdblquote  an animal you have never seen before.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Schmidt used the schema concept to describe two control components involved in the learning and control of skills. Both are characterized as based on abstract rules. The first is the }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i GMP,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  which, as just \u173 ?described, is the control mechanism responsible for controlling the movement coordination patterns of classes of actions, such as throwing, kicking, walking, and running. The second component is the }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i motor response schema,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  which is responsible for providing the specific rules governing the performance of a skill in a given situation. Thus, the motor response schema provides parameters to the GMP.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The schema theory provides an explanation for how well a person can }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i adapt}{\fs20  to new situations or environmental contexts. People can successfully perform a skill requiring movements that have not been made in that same way before. For example, when you walk in a crowded mall or return a tennis serve, characteristics of the situation change in ways that you have not previously experienced. It is possible to perform the skill successfully in these situations because you can use the rules from the motor response schema to generate appropriate parameter characteristics; you add these to the GMP to perform the skill.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Schmidt\rquote s schema theory claims to }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i solve the \u173 ?degrees of freedom problem}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  in movement coordination through an executive control operation that \u173 ?organizes motor programs and schemas. An important emphasis in this approach is the abstract, or general, nature of what is stored in the control \u173 ?
center. The GMP and motor response schema work \u173 ?together to provide the specific movement characteristics needed to initiate an action in a given situation. The action initiation is an open-loop control process. However, once movement is initiated, feedback can influence its course if there is sufficient time to process the feedback and alter the movement in progress.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Testing the invariant relative time feature.}
{\fs20 \u8194\'20\line Researchers have attempted to provide empirical \u173 ?support for motor program\'d0based control by investigating Schmidt\rquote s claim that a generalized motor \u173 ?
program controls a class of actions defined by specific invariant features. Of the proposed invariant features, relative time has generated the most research interest. Support for the invariance of this feature has come from many experiments investigating several \u173 ?
different skills, such as typing, gait, handwriting, \u173 ?prehension, and sequences of key presses, among others. (For reviews of this \u173 ?
evidence, see Heuer, 1991; Schmidt, 1985, 1988, 2003; Shea & Wulf, 2005.)\par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Researchers typically have investigated relative time invariance by observing changes in relative time across a range of values of an associated parameter, such as overall duration or speed. The most commonly cited research example in this regard is a study by Shapiro, Zernicke, Gregor, and Diestel (1981) in which people walked and ran at different speeds on a treadmill. The researchers were interested in the percentages of the total \line step cycle time\u8239 ?}
{\fs20 (i.e., relative time) that would characterize the\u8239 ?four components, or phases, of the step cycle at\u8239 ?each treadmill speed (i.e., the overall duration \u173 ?
parameter). Their hypothesis was that if relative time is invariant for the generalized motor program involved in controlling walking and/or running gait patterns, then the percentages for a specific gait component should remain constant across the different speeds.\par The results were consistent with the hypothesis of relative time invariance (see figure 5.5). As gait sped up or slowed down (at least up to 6 km/hr and beyond 8 km/hr), the percentage of time accounted for by each step cycle component remained essentially the same for different speeds. The differences between the relative time characteristics of walking and running are especially notable in the pie charts in the (b) section of figure 5.5}
{\fs20 . The pie charts show the relative time percentages for the average of the walking speeds and the running speeds for each of the four step cycle phases. Because the relative time percentages differed between walking and running, the authors concluded that two }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i different}{\fs20  \line motor programs control walking and running gaits. Within each gait pattern, the overall duration (i.e., }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 speed) parameter could be increased or slowed down while the relative timing among the components of the step cycle was maintained.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Dynamical Systems Theory\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In sharp contrast to the motor program}{\fs20 \'d0based \u173 ?theory of motor control is an approach commonly \u173 ?referred to as }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 dynamical systems theory}{\fs20  (sometimes referred to as }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i dynamic pattern theory, coordination dynamics theory, ecological theory,}
{\fs20  and }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i action theory}{\fs20 ). The basis for this theoretical viewpoint is a multidisciplinary perspective involving physics, \u173 ?
biology, chemistry, and mathematics. Proponents of this theory see human movement control as a complex system that behaves in ways similar to those of any complex biological or physical system. As a complex system, human motor control is seen from the perspective of }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i nonlinear dynamics;}{\fs20  \line this means that behavioral changes over time do not \u173 ?follow a continuous, linear progression, but make sudden abrupt changes. For example, in the physical world, when the temperature of water is increased gradually there is a specific temperature (100}
{\fs20 \'a1}{\fs20 C) at which the water boils; its behavior abruptly changes. This type of change represents a }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
nonlinear behavior}{\fs20 .\par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 Those who study dynamical systems theory \line are particularly interested in how a system changes \line over time from one stable state to another because of the influence of a particular variable. In \u173 ?
addition, \line they are interested in identifying physical and mathematical laws that govern such behavior. \u173 ?Although this approach has been used to model many complex systems in the physical world (see Gleick, 1987), only since the 1980s has it captured the attention of scientists interested in understanding and explaining human movement control.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw1\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Nonlinear changes in movement behavior.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \u8194\'20A \u173 ?series of experiments by Scott Kelso and his colleagues established for movement scientists that a systematic change in the level of one variable can cause a nonlinear behavioral change in human \u173 ?
coordinated movement (e.g., Kelso, 1984; Kelso & Scholz, 1985). In these experiments participants began moving their right and left index \u173 ?
fingers at a specified rate of speed in one stable coordination state, or pattern, described as an }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw1
antiphase}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  relationship (sometimes \u173 ?referred to as an }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw1 out-of-phase}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  relationship). This means that the muscle groups controlling the right and left fingers were operating simultaneously but in opposite ways: when the right finger was flexed, the left \u173 ?
finger was extended, similar to the motion of windshield wipers in some vehicles. Quantitatively, the \u173 ?fingers were 180}{\f5\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw1\nosupersub
\'a1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  out of phase with each other throughout the movement cycle. The participants systematically increased the speed of their finger movements by keeping their finger speed consistent with that of a metronome controlled by the experimenters. The result was that at a specific speed the finger movements spontaneously shifted to a second stable coordination state, or pattern, described as an \u173 ?\u173 ?}
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw1 in-phase}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  relationship between the two fingers, where both were flexed or extended at the same time (i.e., 0 or 360}
{\f5\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw1\nosupersub \'a1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  in phase with \line each other). }{\fs20 It}
{\fs20 \rquote }{\fs20 s important to note here that the actual speed at which the coordination pattern change will occur varies from person to person. The important point here is that every person will make the change at a certain speed.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd2\expndtw9 You can experience this spontaneous, non-\line }{\fs20 linear coordination change yourself by making two fists with your hands and putting them on your desk or tabletop so that the little \u173 ?
finger side of your fist rests on the desktop. Extend your two index fingers so that they face forward. Then begin to move them side-to-side (keep them parallel to the desktop) in the same way that was done in the Kelso experiment.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The shift to the in-phase coordination state occurred during the }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i transition}{\fs20  between the stable \u173 ?
antiphase and in-phase states. The transition was a mixture of both \u173 ?antiphase and in-phase coordination patterns.}{\fs20  But at\u8239 ?
slower speeds, only an antiphase pattern occurred, whereas at faster speeds, only an in-phase pattern occurred. Thus, a linear increase in movement speed led to a nonlinear change in the fundamental coordination pattern of movement between the two index fingers. }
{\fs20 That is, no notable coordination pattern changes occur as speed increases within a range from slow to fast and then the pattern change occurs rather abruptly at one specific speed.}
{\fs16 \par }{\fs20 When viewed from the perspective of coordination patterns, these experiments established that distinct coordination patterns can }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i spontaneously}{\fs20  develop as a function of a change in one specific \u173 ?variable; which in this case was movement speed. In the finger-movement task used in the Kelso experiments, the antiphase and in-phase finger-movement relationships represent stable coordination patterns. The importance of these experiments is that they provided an initial step in the investigation of coordination changes that can occur without resorting to a mechanism such as a motor program to specify movement characteristics for each coordination pattern.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 These spontaneous coordination pattern changes are not limited to laboratory tasks. They also have been found for motor skills involved in sports and daily activities. For example, front-crawl strokes in swimming exhibit spontaneous arm coordination pattern changes at a specific swimming speed \u173 ?
(Seifert, Chollet, & Bardy, 2004; Seifert et al., 2015). Another example is the change from a walking to a running coordination pattern that spontaneously occurs at a specific speed. The experiment by Shapiro et al. (1981), which was discussed earlier in this chapter, was an early demonstration of this spontaneous gait pattern change. Since that experiment, the walk-to-run and, conversely, the run-to-walk gait changes that occur as a function of speed have been demonstrated numerous times and have become the basis for an increasing amount of research (e.g., \u173 ?
Abdolvahab & Carello, 2015; \u173 ?Diedrich & Warren, 1995, 1998; \u173 ?Farinatti & Monteiro, 2010; Wagenaar & van Emmerik, 1994). We will discuss this spontaneous gait change phenomenon in more detail in chapter 7.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Stability and Attractors\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 At the heart of the dynamical systems view is the \u173 ?concept of }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 stability}{\fs20
. In dynamic terms, stability refers to the behavioral steady state of a system. It is important to note that this use of this term is \u173 ?
different from the concept of invariance. As used here, stability incorporates the notion of variability by noting that when a system is slightly perturbed, it will return spontaneously to a stable state.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 By observing characteristics of a stable state, scientists can gain understanding of the variables that influence a system to behave as it does. For \u173 ?
example, in the reciprocal rhythmic finger movements in the Kelso experiment just described, the researchers observed behavioral stability when the fingers were in antiphase and in-phase relationships with each other. These two stable states indicate two patterns of coordinated movement. Between these states, as finger speed increased, a }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i phase transition}{\fs20  occurred during which instability characterized the behavioral patterns. The instability continued until finger speed reached a point at which a new stable state spontaneously occurred.\par The stable behavioral steady states of systems are known as }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 attractors}{\fs20  (or }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i attractor states}{\fs20 ). In terms of human coordinated movement, attractors are }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i preferred behavioral states,}{\fs20  such as the in-phase and antiphase states for rhythmic finger movements in the Kelso experiment. }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i Attractors represent stable regions of operation around which \u173 ?behavior typically occurs when a system is allowed to operate in its preferred manner.}
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Consider two examples of the presence of attractors for common motor skills. When people locomote at a speed of 3 mi/hr (i.e., 4.8 km/hr), the arms and legs are }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw5 \ldblquote attracted to\rdblquote  a coordination relationship that }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3\u173 ?produces a walking gait. This gait pattern represents the preferred behavioral state for engaging in a locomotion action at this particular speed. But when people locomote at a speed of 10 mi/hr (16 km/hr), the walking gait is not the preferred locomotion state. At this speed, most people run, which, as you saw in figure 5.5, involves a coordination pattern that is different from a walking gait pattern.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 The second example is postural coordination patterns. According to Bardy and his colleagues (e.g., Bardy, Ouiller, Lagarde, & Stoffregen, 2007) there are two stable patterns of postural coordination, as determined by the relationship between the movements of the hips (i.e., the joints that influence trunk movement) and ankles: an in-phase and antiphase pattern. These two patterns are analogous to the rhythmic finger-movement patterns described ear}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 lier, which means that the hips and ankles both exhibit }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 flexion in the in-phase pattern, but one joint extends while the other flexes during the antiphase pattern. Each of these patterns characterize standing postural control coordination in situations in which a person is trying to maintain standing balance on an unstable \line surface, as would occur when you are standing in a moving bus. From a dynamical systems theory perspective, the transition from one coordination pattern to the other (in response to the movement of the bus) occurs automatically and spontaneously because the in-phase and antiphase modes of the postural coordination components (the hips and ankles) establish the \ldblquote preferred\rdblquote  pattern.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Finally, attractor states are not only stable states of coordinated movement, but also optimally }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3
energy-efficient}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  states. This means that when a person is moving at a preferred rate or using a preferred coordination pattern, that person uses less energy than he or she would if moving at a nonpreferred rate.\par }
\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Order and Control Parameters}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Proponents of the dynamical systems view place a priority on developing formal nonlinear equations of motion that specify the stability and loss of stability of movement coordination patterns during motor control, learning, and development. To develop these equations, scientists must identify the variables \u173 ?
responsible for and associated with coordination. Primary among these variables are }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 order parameters}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  (sometimes the term }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 collective variables}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  is used). These are variables that define the overall behavior of a \u173 ?
system. The order parameters enable a coordinated pattern of movement that can be reproduced and distinguished from other patterns.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Because }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i order parameters define a movement pattern,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  it is essential to identify specific types. The most prominent of the order parameters identified by researchers is }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i relative phase}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  for rhythmic movements. Relative phase, which we briefly discussed in chapter 2, refers to a quantified value that represents the movement relationship between two movement segments. For the rhythmic finger-movement task in the Kelso (1984) \u173 ?
experiment, the relative phase for the in-phase movement relationship was 360}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 (which is the same\u8239 ?as 0}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ); the relative phase for the antiphase \u173 ?
movement relationship was 180}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 . These two relative phases were determined by establishing that the maximum adduction of a finger had a phase value of 360}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  (i.e., 0}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ), and the maximum abduction had a phase value of 180}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 . On the basis of a common starting point, the relative phase was then \u173 ?
calculated as the difference between the phase values of the two fingers at any point during the movement.\par }{\fs20 To apply the description from chapter 2 of the calculation of relative phase to this rhythmic \line finger-movement task, consider the following. For the in-phase movement, both fingers had a \u173 ?
common starting point of maximum adduction (i.e., 360}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20 ). The fingers moved together to a maximum abduction position (180}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20 ) and then returned to the initial maximum adduction position. At any time during the fingers}
{\fs20 \rquote  movement, they had a \u173 ?relative phase of 360}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20 , indicating that both fingers are at \line the same abduction position. The opposite holds for the antiphase pattern. At any point, the one finger is abducting the same amount as the other is adducting, which means the two fingers have a relative phase of 180}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \'a1}{\fs20 . \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Another way to consider this phase relationship is from the perspective of the amount of simultaneous adduction and/or \u173 ?
abduction movement. When moving in-phase with each other, both fingers abduct or adduct the same amount at the same time; when moving antiphase, both fingers move the same amount simultaneously, but one is adducting while the other is abducting.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 The }{\f4\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-3 control parameter}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  represents the variable that when increased or decreased will influence the stability and character of the order parameter. For example, in the Kelso experiment, movement \u173 ?
frequency (i.e., speed) was the control parameter. \u173 ?As the movement frequency was systematically \u173 ?increased by the metronome, the phase relationship between the two fingers underwent distinct changes. That is, the in-phase relationship was maintained }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 (i.e., stable)}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  through several frequencies, but then began to destabilize as frequency continued to increase. During an intermediate period neither an in-phase nor an antiphase relationship was detectable. }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 However, as the frequency \u173 ?continued to increase, there was a critical \u173 ?frequency at which the new antiphase relationship emerged and became stable. The shift from one stable pattern to another stable pattern is known as a }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i phase transition.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par From an experimental point of view, the control parameter is important to identify because it becomes the basis for assessing the stability of a pattern of coordination and for shifting a pattern of coordination from one stable state to another. From an applied perspective, the control parameter may provide insights into a person}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \rquote s coordination characteristics that might not otherwise be observed. \par }{\fs20 An example of a situation in which a practitioner could vary the control parameter was reported in a study by}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  van Emmerik and Wagenaar (1996). They demonstrated that Parkinson\rquote s disease patients had more difficulty than healthy age-matched control participants in adapting a specific coordination \u173 ?
pattern while walking to gradually increasing speeds (i.e., the control parameter) on a treadmill. In this study, the relative phase (i.e., the order parameter) of interest was based on the relationship \u173 ?
between the arm and leg swings while walking. The researchers concluded from their results that the \u173 ?assessment of the stability of the phase relationship for the arm and leg swings at various walking speeds provides a sensitive technique to diagnose and detect early stages of Parkinson\rquote s disease.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb253\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Self-organization.}{\fs20 \u8194\'20}
{\fs20 An important element of the }{\f5\fs20\b0\i0 dynamical systems}{\fs20  perspective is the concept of }{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
self-organization}{\fs20 .}{\f4\fs20\b\i0  }{\fs20 This means that when certain conditions characterize a situation, a specific stable pattern of behavior emerges. Many examples of self-organization exist within the physical world that illustrate applications of this concept to the human movement domain. For example, there is no hurricane program in the universe, but hurricanes commonly occur. However, they occur only when certain wind and water temperature conditions \u173 ?
exist. When these variables achieve certain characteristics, a hurricane will self-organize in an identifiable pattern that distinguishes it from a tropical depression or any other weather system.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 When applied to human movement coordination, the concept of self-organization means that when certain conditions characterize a situation, a specific pattern of limb movement emerges. Thus, rather than being specified by a motor program, the coordinated pattern of movement self-organizes within the framework of the characteristics of \u173 ?
environmental conditions, the task demands, and limb dynamics. For example, in the bimanual finger-movement task performed in the Kelso experiments, the in-phase coordination pattern self-organized as a function of the movement speed (i.e., the control parameter). This same type of self-organization is seen for the walk-to-run, or run-to-walk, gait transitions that \u173 ?
occur as gait speed increases or decreases and for the arm coordination change that occurs as swim speed increases (see, for example, Seifert, Chollet, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 & Bardy, 2004).\par }\pard\plain \s12\f4\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb253\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Coordinative Structures; Muscle Synergies\par }\pard\plain \s11\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Another important aspect of the dynamical systems view relates to the unit of behavior that is controlled. Proponents of the view assert that skilled action results when a person\rquote s nervous system \u173 ?
constrains }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i functionally specific collections of muscles and joints}{\fs20  to act cooperatively, so that the person can achieve an action goal according to the dictates of the situation. An individual may develop these performance synergies, called }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 coordinative structures}{\fs20 ,}{\fs20  through practice or experience, or they may exist naturally.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 One example of a coordinative structure is the muscles and joints (the degrees of freedom to be controlled) involved in the action of reaching and grasping an object. The groups of muscles and joints that must act together to enable a person }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4 to successfully reach and grasp an object are }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \ldblquote converted\rdblquote  through practice into a task-specific ensemble. \par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd2\expndtw8 An analogy here may help. The term \ldblquote task-}{\fs20 specific ensemble\rdblquote  can be thought of as analogous to singing groups, commonly called \ldblquote ensembles,\rdblquote  \line in which many individuals sing specific parts of a specific song; all the individual singers work \line }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 together cooperatively (i.e., synergistically) to achieve \line }{\fs20 a specific goal. Similarly, coordinative structures are ensembles of muscles and joints that work cooperatively to allow a person to achieve a specific action goal, such as grasping an object. \par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 For the motor control system the existence of coordinative structures reduces the degrees of freedom that the system must control. Rather than having to control the many degrees of freedom represented by the many muscles and joints involved in performing an action, the motor control system can control one ensemble of muscles and joints. In this sense, the control system for a specific movement can be less complex than would be suggested by the number of degrees of freedom that need to be controlled. For the reach-and-grasp action the activation of the coordinative structure begins when a person has the intention to reach and grasp a cup and the environmental conditions specify that this action should occur. Then, in accordance with the characteristics of the limb and of the environmental constraints, the coordinative structure self-organizes to carry out the action.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 An important behavioral benefit of coordinative structures is that they allow a person to achieve an action goal even when a muscle or joint that is a part of the structure is not able to function normally. For example, if you have a cast on your leg that keeps your knee from bending, you are able to walk up or down the stairs. This is possible because some of the muscles in the ensemble of muscles and joints (i.e., the coordinative structure) associated with walking up and down the stairs will activate in a way that compensates for the lack of involvement by muscles that can\rquote t normally function because of the cast. Consider this compensatory activity as similar to what occurs in sports teams when one of the players is not able to perform at his or her best, but the team performs well because players \ldblquote step up\rdblquote  and perform at a higher level than they typically perform.\par }
\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Coordinative structures can be intrinsic or developed through practice. }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i Intrinsic coordinative structures}
{\fs20  are involved in actions such as walking, running, and bimanual coordination. When we perform these actions, the muscles and joints of the limbs involved have a natural tendency to demonstrate interlimb coordination patterns that have characterized our performance of them since early in life. For example, when performing a skill involving \u173 ?
bimanual coordination, which requires the simultaneous use of both arms and hands, both infants (see,\u8239 ?for example, Corbetta & Thelen, 1996) and adults (see Kelso, Southard, & Goodman, 1979, for instance) typically demonstrate a similar natural \u173 ?
tendency to move the arms and hands in synchrony\'d1that is, \u173 ?simultaneously both spatially and temporally. This means that when people first learn to perform a tennis serve, which requires each arm to simultaneously move in different ways, their initial tendency is to move their arms in the same way at the same time.}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 In contrast, }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 coordinative structures developed through practice}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  become new combinations of muscles and joints that act together to produce a \u173 ?coordination pattern that will allow the achievement of an action goal. The tennis serve just described is a good example of the development of \u173 ?
a\u8239 ?new coordinative structure as a result of extensive practice. Another example was described by Seifert, \line Chollet, and Allard (2004) for swimmers. As front-crawl swimmers achieved elite status, they began to \line }
{\fs20 demonstrate a stroke speed and length relationship with breathing frequency that allowed them to adapt to race situation demands more successfully than less skilled swimmers. Similar development of coordinative structures was found for skilled drummers as a result of practicing asymmetric bimanual coordination  patterns (Fuji, Kudo, }
{\fs20 Ohtsuki}{\fs20 , & Oda, 2010).\par For the learning of certain skills, the intrinsic coordinative structures can lead to initial perfor-mance difficulties, as in the case of learning a tennis serve. However, after overcoming these initial difficulties, the person}
{\fs20 \rquote s performance of the skill will benefit from the newly developed coordinative structure, because it will allow him or her to achieve an action goal even though some slight perturbation occurs during the action. For example, if a tennis player is serving, and during the serve a gust of wind makes the ball deviate from its intended path, the player can quickly and easily adjust the movements involved in his or her serving action and achieve a successful serve. Similarly, if a person is jogging on a sidewalk and must step over a curb, the jogger can quickly and easily adjust movement characteristics of his or her gait pattern to avoid tripping while maintaining the jogging coordination pattern.\par }
\pard\plain \s14\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb180\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs51\f6\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw1\cf0\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Perception and action coupling.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 Proponents of the }{\f5\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw1 dynamical systems}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1
 view emphasize the interaction of the performer and the physical environment in which the skill is performed. From a motor control perspective, this interaction involves perception and movement variables that must be taken into account in any attempt to explain the mechanisms involved in the control of motor skills. The }
{\f5\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw1 dynamical systems}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  theory proposes that this interaction, which is referred to as }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw1 perception}{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw1 -action \u173 ?coupling}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 , is an essential element in accounting for skillful performance. The perception part of the interaction detects and uses critical invariant information in an environment (e.g., the amount of time until an object contacts the person, or vice versa); the action part involves the setting and regulating of movement control features that enable the person to achieve the action goal (e.g., kinematic and kinetic components of movements).}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1\super 2}{\*\cs52\fs16\super 2}{\fs16 For an excellent discussion of perception-action coupling \u173 ?and its application to sport skill performance, see Buekers, \u173 ?
Montagne, and Laurent (1999). }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \par }\pard\plain \s13\f5\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 An example of a perceptual variable involved in this type of coupling process is known by the Greek letter }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i
tau}{\fs20  (}{\fs20\u964 ?}{\fs20 ), which is related to the time to contact between an object and a person}{\fs20 \rquote s eye. (We will discuss }
{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  further in chapters 6 and 8.) Researchers have demonstrated that }{\*\cs49\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  guides actions such as steering a car, catching a ball, hitting a ball, jumping from a platform, and performing the long jump (Lee, 2009; Lee et al., 2009). As a person gains experience, the perceptual variable couples with the dynamics of movement so that a distinct coordination pattern can be reproduced and modified as needed.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 Some additional examples of perception-action coupling include the coordination pattern people use to get on or over an obstacle, climb stairs, and go through a doorway. Researchers have found that \line obstacles in a person}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \rquote s pathway, stairs, and door openings specify size-related information that a person perceives in terms of an invariant relationship between an object\rquote s size and her or his own leg length (in the case of obstacles and stairs) or \line body size (in the case of door openings). Thus the person will step or climb over the obstacle on the basis of this perceived relationship, choose one of various stair-climbing options, and walk through a doorway sideways or face-forward depending on this perceived relationship between the environmental feature and his or her own body size\'d0related feature. The reciprocal fit between the characteristics of a person and the characteristics of the environment that permit specific actions, such as stairs having the physical characteristics to permit stair climbing, are referred to as }
{\*\cs50\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw1 affordances}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  in the perception-action coupling literature (Gibson, 1979). Learning to detect affordances is central to motor control and learning from this perspective.}
