{\fs19 Looking at the Degrees of Freedom Problem at the Level of Muscles and Joints\par }\pard\plain \s32\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 We know that there are 792 muscles in the human body that can act to make the one hundred joints behave in different ways. And each joint has mechanical characteristics that define its degrees of freedom for movement. On the basis of these features, \u173 ?
Turvey (1990) put the coordination control problem into perspective this way. If all the joints were only hinge joints like the elbow, there would be one hundred mechanical degrees of freedom to be controlled at the joint level. But if two specific characteristics, such as position and velocity, needed to be defined for these }
{\fs18 types of }{\fs18 joints to carry out a specific act, the degrees of freedom would increase to two hundred.\par }\pard\plain \s33\f5\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw2 Consider the following examples. If you were seated at a table and decided to pick up a drinking glass in front of you on the table, the number of degrees of freedom involved just in terms of the number of joints (this does not take into account the number of ways each joint can move) would be \line the shoulder joint (1), elbow joint (1), wrist joint (1), and all the finger (3 joints }
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw2\u215 ?}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw2  4 fingers }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw2 =}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw2  12 joints) and thumb (3) joints. The total number of joints that need to be controlled for this simple action is 18. Now suppose that the drinking glass in front of you is very large and requires two hands to pick it up. The nervous system must now control at least double the number of degrees of freedom compared to the one-hand situation. In both cases, you probably would not have any difficulty coordinating the joints of one or two limbs to achieve the action goal. But, if we consider these tasks from the level of neuromuscular control where the many degrees of freedom must be controlled to operate in very specific ways, the simple task of picking up a drinking glass becomes a very complex one. Yet, the nervous system handles this complex operation. Theories of motor control need to be able to explain how the nervous system does this.\par }
