{\fs18 Early Greek philosophers such as }{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i Plato}{\fs18  talked about a person}{\fs18 \rquote s creation of an \ldblquote image\rdblquote  of an act preceding the action itself.\par }
{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i William James}{\fs18  (1890) alluded to Plato when he stated that to perform an action, a person must first form a clear \ldblquote image\rdblquote  of that action.}
{\fs18 \par }{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i Karl Lashley}{\fs18\expnd1\expndtw3  (1917) is regarded as the first person to use the actual term }
{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i motor program.}{\fs18\expnd1\expndtw3  He initially viewed motor programs as \ldblquote intention[s] to act,}
{\fs18\expnd1\expndtw3 \rdblquote  but later described them as \ldblquote generalized schemata of action which determine the sequence of specific acts\rdblquote  (Lashley, 1951, \line p. 122). He proposed that these schemata were organized to provide central control of movement patterns.\par }
{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i Sir Frederick Bartlett}{\fs18  (1932) implied that a motor program exists when he used the term }{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i
schema}{\fs18  to describe internal representations and organizations of movements.\par }{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i Miller, Galanter, and Pribram }
{\fs18 (1960) proposed the notion of a \ldblquote Plan,\rdblquote  which was \ldblquote essentially the same as a program for a computer\rdblquote  (}
{\fs18 p. 16), and was responsible for controlling the sequence of events of an action.\par }{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i Franklin Henry}{\fs18
 (Henry }{\fs18 & Rogers, 1960) gave the motor program concept a needed conceptual and empirical boost. He hypothesized that the \ldblquote neural pattern for a specific and well-coordinated motor act is controlled by a stored program that is used to direct the neuromotor details of its perfor-mance\rdblquote  (p.\u8239 ?
449). Henry\rquote s concept of the motor program was also that of a computer program. He proposed that when initiated, the program controls the exact movement details, with essentially no modifications possible during the execution of the movement.}
{\fs18 \par }{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i Stephen Keele}{\fs18  (1968) offered a view similar to Henry\rquote s by defining the motor program as \ldblquote a set of muscle commands that are structured before a movement sequence begins, and that allow . . . the entire sequence to be carried out uninfluenced by peripheral feedback\rdblquote  }
{\fs18 (p. 387).\par }{\*\cs49\fs18\b0\i Richard Schmidt}{\fs18  (1975) proposed that the motor program is not specific muscle commands, but is an abstract memory-based representation of a class of actions, with each class defined by invariant features. Because of these characteristics he called his version the \ldblquote generalized\rdblquote  motor program.\par }
