{\*\cs50\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 Motor Program Theory}{\fs18  The relative time structure of a coordination pattern distinguishes one generalized motor program from another. Because walking and running gaits are characterized by different relative time structures, they are controlled by different generalized motor programs. The walk-to-run gait pattern change occurs at a certain speed because the person chooses to change from the program that controls walking to the program that controls running.}
{\fs18 \par }{\*\cs50\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 Dynamical Systems Theory}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1  Interlimb and body coor}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3
dination patterns self-organize as a function of specific control parameter values and environmental conditions. For walking and running gait patterns, }
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3 speed is a critical control parameter. The walk-to-run }{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3 gait transition involves a competition between two attractors. At slow speeds, the primary attractor state is a walking coordination pattern. But as walking speed increases, there is a certain range of speeds at which this attractor state loses stability, which means that for this range of speeds, the walking pattern \u173 ?
undergoes some change as a running coordination pattern self-organizes and eventually becomes the stable attractor state for gait at a certain speed.}
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s35\f4\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb220\sa0\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
